<br>
I was wrong about Sephiroth, sort of.  His intentions and actions were what made him cool, not his personality.  I tried to attack him for being a bad antagonist because of his rather stereotypical bad guy personality, but I guess I wasn't being real rational in my argument.<br>
<br>
Kefka is more less the same.  The things he said and did made him cool, not his personality.  I don't stand by this argument all that much either...<br>
<br>
Even so, I fully stand by my nostalgia factor argument.  Every person in the world is likely guilty of it, videogame related or not.  I brought it up in many topics, but it's true, nostalgia is a big factor in how we judge things.  After all, in order to compare things, we need something to compare to.  For example, gamers will compare FFX to FF6.  However, when they're comparing them, they're completely biased, though they don't know it, err, most of them.  It's because when they played FF6, that was a different time and place, and they recall many memories with it.  Had they played BOTH games at the same time such a long time ago, perhaps they WOULD like FFX better, or it's more likely they would.  This probably is confusing, but it's true.  I'll never back off of this argument. <p><hr>
"I'm not afraid of being taken over by computers though, because the thing is, computers cannot resist. You can always smash 'em up, and they're totally defenseless. All we need are more people with hammers." <i>- Thom Yorke</i>

